    <h1>Desert Biome Human Interaction Summary</h1>
    <div class="summary">
        <p class="info">In the hot desert biome, human interaction can take many forms. Here are some key aspects:</p>
        <ul class="info">
            <li>**Observation of Flora and Fauna**: Unique species like cacti and the fennec fox.</li>
            <li>**Outdoor Activities**: Hiking, camping, and photography opportunities abound.</li>
            <li>**Research and Education**: Many scientists study desert adaptations and survival strategies.</li>
            <li>**Conservation Efforts**: Participation in local initiatives to protect fragile ecosystems.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/r9RL9ISACTs/maxresdefault.jpg" alt="Cacti">
            <p>Cacti: Adapted to store water and thrive in arid conditions.</p>
            <img src="https://preview.redd.it/a29rh1aswkdz.png?width=1080&crop=smart&auto=webp&s=9e186c9e8d2f3281a875152b13df24f9e2770f84" alt="Fennec Fox">
            <p>Fennec Fox: Known for its large ears, which help dissipate heat.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="info">Here are some interesting facts about human interaction with the desert biome:</p>
        <ul class="info">
            <li>Many desert plants can survive for months without rain, storing water in their tissues.</li>
            <li>Desert ecosystems are incredibly diverse, hosting plants and animals specially adapted to harsh conditions.</li>
            <li>Some people visit deserts to experience the unique beauty of the night sky, as deserts often have minimal light pollution.</li>
            <li>Indigenous cultures have developed sustainable practices to live harmoniously with the desert environment for centuries.</li>
            <li>Tourism in desert areas can boost local economies, but it's important to balance it with conservation efforts.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
